# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agkud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:agkud/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:agkud/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:agkud/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:agkud/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:agkud/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:agkud/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:agkud/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:agkud/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:agkud/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:agkud/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:agkud/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:agkud/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:agkud/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:agkud/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:agkud/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:agkud/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:agkud/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:agkud/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:agkud/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:agkud/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:agkud/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:agkud/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:agkud/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:agkud/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:agkud/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:agkud/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:agkud/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:agkud/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:agkud/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:agkud/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:agkud/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:agkud/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:agkud/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:agkud/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:agkud/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:agkud/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:agkud/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:agkud/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:agkud/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:agkud/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:agkud/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:agkud/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:agkud/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:agkud/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:agkud/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:agkud/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:agkud/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:agkud/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:agkud/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:agkud/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:agkud/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:agkud/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:agkud/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:agkud/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:agkud/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:agkud/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:agkud/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:agkud/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:agkud/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:agkud/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:agkud/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:agkud/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:agkud/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:agkud/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:agkud/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:agkud/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:agkud/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:agkud/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:agkud/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:agkud/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:agkud/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:agkud/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:agkud/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:agkud/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:agkud/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:agkud/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:agkud/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:agkud/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:agkud/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:agkud/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:agkud/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:agkud/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:agkud/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:agkud/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:agkud/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:agkud/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:agkud/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:agkud/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:agkud/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:agkud/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:agkud/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:agkud/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:agkud/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:agkud/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:agkud/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:agkud/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:agkud/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:agkud/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:agkud/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:agkud/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:agkud/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:agkud/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:agkud/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:agkud/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:agkud/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:agkud/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:agkud/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:agkud/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:agkud/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:agkud/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:agkud/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:agkud/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:agkud/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:agkud/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:agkud/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:agkud/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:agkud/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:agkud/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:agkud/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:agkud/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:agkud/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:agkud/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:agkud/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:agkud/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:agkud/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:agkud/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:agkud/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:agkud/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:agkud/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:agkud/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:agkud/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:agkud/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:agkud/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:agkud/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:agkud/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:agkud/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:agkud/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:agkud/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:agkud/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:agkud/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:agkud/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:agkud/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:agkud/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:agkud/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:agkud/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:agkud/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:agkud/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:agkud/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The word is a compound of the Iberian languages' words for 'water' (*agua* in Castilian, i.e.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Spanish; *aigua* in Catalan; *água* in Portuguese; *auga* in Galician) and 'burning'/'fiery' (*ardiente* in Castilian; *ardent* in Catalan; *ardente* in Portuguese and Galician).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] A comparable word in English is "firewater", though the English term is colloquial or humorous, whereas *aguardiente* is stylistically neutral in Spanish.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] However, *aguardiente* and *aguardente* are not legal denominations.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Instead, different categories of *aguardientes* (spirits in the English version) are established according to raw materials.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In the Spanish version, wine spirit (brandy) is *aguardiente de vino*, fruit spirit is *aguardiente de fruta*, grain spirit (other than whiskey and neutral grain spirit) is *aguardiente de cereales*, etc.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Some drinks named *aguardiente* or similar are of different origins (grape pomace, sugarcane); other drinks with the same origin may have different names (clairin, brandy).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Brazil, a beverage known as *cachaça* or *pinga*, considered distinct from traditional *aguardiente*, is made from sugarcane.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Cachaça* has two varieties: unaged (white) and aged (gold).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] White *cachaça* is usually bottled immediately after distillation and tends to be cheaper.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is often used to prepare caipirinha and other beverages in which *cachaça* is an ingredient.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Dark *cachaça*, usually seen as the "premium" variety, is aged in wood barrels and is meant to be drunk neat.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Traditionally, no herbs are used to flavor the *cachaça*; its flavor is influenced by the fermentation agent, time spent in the cask, or the type of wood from which the barrel is made.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] One form that can be qualified as moonshine is known as "Maria Louca" ("Crazy Mary").
[src:agkud/aguardiente] This is *aguardiente*, made in jails by inmates.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It can be made from many cereals, ranging from beans to rice, or whatever can be converted into alcohol, be it fruit peels or candy, using improvised and illegal equipment.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Grogue, also known as grogu or grogo (derived from English grog), is a Cape Verdean alcoholic beverage, an *aguardiente* made from sugarcane processed in a trapiche.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Its production is fundamentally artisanal, and nearly all the sugarcane is used in producing grogue.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Chile, *aguardiente* is an alcoholic beverage of 45% and higher ABV (beverages with over 55% ABV are illegal).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is made, like Italian grappa, by distilling the grape residue, primarily the skins and pulp (**hollejo**) plus the stems (**escobajos**) and seeds, left over from winemaking after pressing the grapes.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is used to make several other flavored liquors, such as the *murtado* or **enmurtillado** (using sun-dried *murtilla*, an orange-reddish wild rose fruit), the **enguindado** (soaking sun-dried morello cherries) and *licor de oro* (flavored with saffron and lemon peel).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Dried mint, peeled walnuts, almonds, and other aromatic herbs are also used to flavor the *aguardiente*.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is mainly consumed by itself or as a base to make *cola de mono* ("monkey tail").
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Colombia, *aguardiente* is an anise-flavored liqueur derived from sugarcane, popular in the Andean region.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Different flavors are obtained by adding different amounts of aniseed, leading to extensive marketing and fierce competition between brands.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Aguardiente* has 24%–29% alcohol content.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Other anise-flavored liqueurs similar to *aguardiente*, but with a lower alcohol content, are also sold.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Since the Spanish era, *aguardiente* has maintained the status of the most popular alcoholic beverage in the Andean regions of Colombia, with the notable exception of the Caribbean region, where rum is most popular.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Generally, *aguardiente* is rarely drunk in cocktails and usually drunk neat.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] On the Caribbean coast, there is a moonshine called "Cococho", an *aguardiente* infamous for the number of blindness cases due to the addition of methanol.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Costa Rica, it is 30% alcohol, with a neutral flavor.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The Costa Rican government tightly controls Guaro to help prevent clandestine production.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Guam and the Mariana Islands, a distilled version of *tubâ* (coconut palm wine introduced from the Philippines) is known as *aguajente* (also *aguayente* or *agi*).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It was prevalent among the Chamorro people, but is largely extinct; the United States banned its manufacture soon after the acquisition of Guam from the Spanish Empire in 1899.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] A local company "Aguayente distillers" has recently installed a commercial still and will soon start distilling liquor from locally grown potatoes.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is also derived from sugar cane, but unlike Colombia, it is left largely unflavoured.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is then taken straight as shots, mulled with cinnamon (*canela* in Spanish) and fruit juices to make the hot cocktail *canelazo*, or mixed with the juice of naranjilla and spices for the hot cocktail *draquita*.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Locally or artisanally made *aguardiente* is commonly called *punta*, "puro" or *trago*, and alcohol content can vary widely, from "mild" *puntas* of about 10% to "strong" of about 40% or higher.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The traditional distillation process produces *aguardiente* as strong as 60 g/L.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Every Ecuadorian province has a slightly different flavor to the *aguardiente* made there, and each province has a different recipe for *canelazo*.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is the most commonly consumed strong alcohol.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Mexico, *aguardiente* goes by many names, including *habanero*.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In the state of Michoacán, *charanda* is a traditional rum-like sugar cane *aguardiente*.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Casa Berreteaga marketed an *aguardiente* called "Berreteaga", which used sugarcane sourced from the Coxcatlan region of Puebla.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Berreteaga was a fortified wine made from rum and sweet wine (usually Muscat) or (uncommonly) a sweet brandy that was then aged in oak barrels.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Portuguese *aguardente* has several varieties.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Aguardente vínica* is distilled from either good quality or undrinkable wine.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is mostly used to fortify wines such as port or aged to make *aguardente velha* (old burning water), a kind of brandy.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Aguardente bagaceira* (mostly known as "bagaço") is made from pomace to prevent waste after the close of wine season.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is usually bootlegged, as most drinkers only appreciate it in its traditional formulation of 50% to 80% ABV.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] A common way to drink it is as *café com cheirinho* ("coffee with a little scent"), a liqueur coffee made with espresso.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In the Azores, this *espresso-aguardente* combination is commonly referred to as *café com música* ("coffee with music").
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Aguardente Medronho* is a variety distilled from the fruit of the *Arbutus unedo* tree.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In Madeira, it is the core ingredient for *poncha*, a beverage around which a festival is based.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Most of the *aguardente* from the region is made from sugarcane.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In certain areas of the Pyrenees in Catalonia, *aiguardent*, as it is known in Catalan, is used as an essential ingredient in the preparation of *tupí*, a type of cheese.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Galicia is renowned for the quality and variety of its *augardentes* (Galician), or *aguardientes* (Spanish), including *augardente de bagazo* (*aguardiente de Orujo*), which is obtained from the distillation of the pomace of grapes, and is clear and colorless.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It typically contains over 50% alcohol, sometimes significantly more, and is still made traditionally in many villages across Galicia today.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Augardente de herbas*, usually yellow, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo* and herbs (*herbas*), with chamomile being a substantial ingredient.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Licor café* (typical distilled drink in the province of Ourense), black in color, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo*, coffee (*café*), and sugar.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] *Crema de augardente* or c*rema de caña* is a cream liqueur based on *augardente*, coffee, cream, milk, and other ingredients.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] In some places in Galicia, a small glass is traditionally taken at breakfast as a tonic before a hard day's work on the land.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The word "*orujo*" is Spanish and not Galician, but is used to distinguish Galician and some Spanish augardentes from those of other countries.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Most of the moonshine in Spain is made as a byproduct of winemaking by distilling the squeezed skins of the grapes.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The essential product is called "*orujo*" or "*aguardiente*" (burning water).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] The homemade versions are usually more potent and have a higher alcoholic content, well over the 40% that the commercial versions typically have.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It is often mixed with herbs, spices, fruits, or other distillates.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] Types include *pacharán*, *licor de café* and *orujo de hierbas* (tea mixed with orujo).
[src:agkud/aguardiente] During the mission and rancho periods of California history, *aguardiente* was made out of mission grapes.
[src:agkud/aguardiente] It was popular during the Gold Rush of 1849.
